\end{document}
```
**How it works:**

1. The `\documentclass` chooses a document class that supports TOC (e.g., `book`, `report`, or `article`).
2. The `\tableofcontents` command is used to typeset the TOC at the desired location in your document.
3. LaTeX will automatically generate the TOC based on the sectioning commands used in your document (e.g., `\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.).
4. If you need more customization options, you can load the `tocloft` package, which provides additional features for tweaking the TOC layout.

**Note:** Make sure to run LaTeX twice (e.g., `latex yourdoc.tex` followed by `latex yourdoc.tex` again) to resolve any cross-references and update the TOC correctly.

This will generate a table of contents with the sectioning headings and page numbers. You can then customize the appearance and layout of the TOC to your liking using various package options and commands.

